<!-- показ одной работы -->
	
	<div style="padding-top:3px; font-size: 1.4rem;"> The paper contains 54 pages, consists of the introduction, 3 sections, conclusion, 71 references and 11 appendices. The aim of this empirical study was investigation of the effect of merger and acquisition on the default risk of the acquiring firm and the factors affecting default probability after the merger. The sample of 484 cross-border and domestic deals completed between 1990 and 2009 was selected from Thomson One Analytics and Thomson Reuters Datastream databases. In this paper we examined the influence of M&amp;A on the default probability of acquiring firm by comparing the difference in pre- and post-merger industry adjusted distance to default and estimated the effect of free cash flow on the default risk of the acquiring firm by running the regression with distance to default as the dependent variable.The following hypotheses of the research were confirmed:1. Industry-adjusted distance to default decreases after the merger and acquisition.2. The driving force behind the increase in the default risk of the acquiring firm following the merger is the presence of the free cash flow at the discretion of the managers.For the estimation of the probability of the default of the firm we employed Merton distance to default model. The results of the comparison of pre- and post-merger industry-adjusted distance to default show that mergers and acquisitions on average lead to decrease in the distance to default of the acquiring firm after the merger on 0.561. Next the effect of geographic diversification on the change in the default risk of the acquiring firm is examined. One can conclude that there are diversification gains from cross-border merger and acquisition since the decrease in the distance to default is present only for domestic mergers. By looking at the effect of the level of acquiring country development on bidder default risk the result shows the negative effect of the level of country development on the industry-adjusted distance to default: only for the developed countries the effect of merger on default risk is significant. Same results hold if we control for the level of development of the target country. The proposition about the difference in the effect of inter- and intra-industry mergers on the change in the default risk of the acquiring firm was rejected: there is an increase in the default probability after the takeover independently of whether the merger was horizontal or not. Finally, the source of financing of the merger and acquisition plays an important role in the change in the distance to default: the takeovers financed through common stock issue lead to the increase in bidder default probability after the deal in contrast to cash financed deals, for which the effect of merger on distance to default is insignificant.In the subsequent analysis the effect of the initial pre-merger default risk of the bidder on the change in the distance to default after takeover was examined. The results show that the increase in the default risk of the firm following the merger and acquisition is inherent only for initially low default-risk firms (firms with highest distance to default), which can be possibly explained by the inability of safe firms to realize fully the diversification gains. Although this effect of the decrease in the distance to default for initially low-risk firms is not attributed to the geographic diversification (there is no difference in the effect of the merger on distance to default of safe firms engaged in domestic and cross-border deals), while one can see that initially high-risk firms benefit from geographic diversification: domestic deals lead to the increase in the default risk of the high-risk firm, while cross-border deals &ndash; don&rsquo;t. On the other hand the effect of merger and acquisition on low-risk can be explained by the level of the development of the acquiring country: for low default risk firms the effect is especially pronounced for the developed countries. The same is true for initially high-risk firms. Thus, one can state the strong connection between the acquirer country level of development, riskiness of the firm and the change in the default risk following the merger.The regression analysis confirmed the presence of negative effect of free cash flow on the change in industry-adjusted distance to default after the merger. The presence of management-equity problem is also confirmed by the significance of profit margin, which is positively related to the change in distance to default after the merger. Among the financial characteristics of the acquiring firm leverage has negative significant effect on distance to default, while acquirer return on assets and size haven&rsquo;t. The target leverage, the difference in the GPD per capita and size of the target and acquiring firm are at the same time insignificant. Concerning the deal characteristics, there is no significant effect of geographic and product diversification on the change in distance to default following the merger, while for tender offers industry-adjusted distance to default decreases after the takeover, and for cash deals it increases after merger and acquisition. The creditor rights are negative and significant only in a few model specifications, while the effect of strength of shareholder right is significant and negative almost in all model specifications: the stronger are the rights of the shareholders, the lower is the distance to default after the merger. Furthermore, for Scandinavian legal origin countries the effect of merger on the change in distance to default is lower than for countries from other legal origins. Last but not least, the effect of agency cost of free cash flow is present only for the acquiring firms with high growth opportunities (high q firms).In conclusion it is worth mentioning that this research does not claim to be indisputable and universal solution of the given problem, connected with the analysis of the effect of mergers and acquisitions on the default risk of the acquiring firm. As any research based on the regression analysis it has limitations. Nevertheless, the current research can be used in addition to the existing literature on effect of mergers and acquisitions on the risk of the acquiring firm and its results can be valuable in business practices and for the creditors as the guidelines in evaluation of the effect of the transaction on the default of the firm. </div>
	
	
